@*
    MODEL DECLARATION IN RAZOR VIEW:
    ********************************
     In ASP.NET Core MVC:
     > The View receives data from the Controller
     > The "model" represents the data sent from the Controller to the View

    In our controller action method, we wrote:

        var allInstruments = _context.Instruments.ToList();
        return View(allInstruments);

    This means we are passing a COLLECTION of Instrument objects to the View.

    Therefore, in the View we must declare the model type, yes we can use either way:

        - Way#1 (Correct - Works Fine): @model List<Instrument>
        - Way#2 (Recommended - Professional): @model IEnumerable<Instrument>

    In the controller, we used: _context.Instruments.ToList()
    which returns a List<Instrument>.

    However, in the View we will use "Way#2": @model IEnumerable<Instrument>

    Why IEnumerable<Instrument> and not using List<Instrument>?
    ***********************************************************
        - IEnumerable<T> represents a collection of items
        - It is more flexible than List<T>
        - It works with List, arrays, and other collection types

    This is a common best practice in ASP.NET Core MVC.
    In simple terms:
        List<T> = specific type
        IEnumerable<T> = general collection (recommended)

    This allows our View to remain flexible and reusable.

    What does this mean?
    ********************
    - IEnumerable<Instrument> represents a collection (list) of Instrument objects
    - It allows us to loop through the data using foreach

    Example usage in the View:

        @foreach (var item in Model)
        {
            <p>@item.Name</p>
        }

    Why IEnumerable instead of List?
    ********************************
    - IEnumerable is more flexible (it works with List, arrays, etc.)
    - It is a common best practice in MVC Views


    IMPORTANT CONCEPT: "COUPLING"
    *****************************
    As we discussed this concept in Advanced OOP With Java course,
    "Coupling" refers to how tightly one part of the code depends on another.

    Tight Coupling (Less Flexible):
    *******************************
        @model List<Instrument>

        - The View depends specifically on List<T>
        - If the Controller changes to return a different collection type,
          the View must also be changed

    Loose Coupling (Recommended):
    *****************************
        @model IEnumerable<Instrument>

        - The View depends on a general abstraction (IEnumerable<T>)
        - It works with ANY collection type (List, Array, IQueryable, etc.)
        - The View becomes more flexible and reusable

    SUMMARY:
    ********
        List<T> = Specific type  (Tightly coupled)
        IEnumerable<T> = General type (Loosely coupled - Recommended)

    This is a common best practice in ASP.NET Core MVC.

    It allows our View to remain flexible, reusable, and easier to maintain.

    IMPORTANT NOTE:
    ***************
    The model type in the View MUST match the data passed from the Controller.

    Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/views/overview
*@

@{
    // C# Code written inside @ { and }
    ViewData["Title"] = "Instruments List";
}

@* Using "IEnumerable" to refer to any type of collection: *@
@model IEnumerable<Instrument>

<div class="text-center">
    <h1 class="display-4">Instruments List</h1>
    <p>Below is the list of all instruments</p>

    @*
        Bootstrap Table:
        ****************
        We use Bootstrap classes to style the table.

        Link:
        https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/content/tables/
    *@
    <table class="table table-striped table-hover">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                @*
                    NOTE:
                    We are displaying a row counter instead of the actual database Id.
                    This is useful for UI readability.
                *@
                <th scope="col">#</th>
                <th scope="col">Instrument</th>
                <th scope="col">Description</th>
                <th scope="col">Price</th>
                <th scope="col">Actions</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            @*
                Looping through the Model collection:
                *************************************

                - "Model" represents the data passed from the controller
                - Each item is of type Instrument
                - We use a foreach loop to render each row

                EMPTY STATE HANDLING:
                *********************
                Before looping through the data, we check if the collection is empty.
                
                Model.Any() returns:
                    - true => if there are records
                    - false => if the collection is empty
                
                 If there are no instruments, 
                 we display a friendly message inside the table.
            *@


            @if (!Model.Any())
            {
                <tr>
                    <td colspan="5" class="text-center">
                        No instruments found.
                    </td>
                    @*
                        NOTE:
                        *****
                        colspan="5" must match the total number of table columns,
                        including the "Actions" column.

                        Otherwise, the table layout may break.
                    *@
                </tr>
            }
            else
            {
                @*
                    Looping through the "Model" collection:
                    ***************************************
                *@
                int row = 1;
                foreach (var instrument in Model)
                {
                    <tr>
                        <th scope="row">@row</th>

                        @* Displaying Instrument properties *@
                        <td>@instrument.Name</td>
                        <td>@instrument.Description</td>

                        @*
                            Formatting Price as Currency:
                            *****************************
                            We use ToString("C") to format the price as a currency value.

                            Example: 2500 => $2,500.00 (based on system culture)

                            "C" stands for Currency format.

                            NOTE:
                            *****
                            The displayed currency symbol and format 
                            depend on the system or application culture settings.

                            This improves readability and provides a better user experience.

                            Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/base-types/standard-numeric-format-strings
                        *@
                        <td>@instrument.Price.ToString("C")</td>
                        @*
                            IMPORTANT:
                            **********
                            Tag Helpers like "asp-action" and "asp-route-id" do NOT work with <button> elements.

                            They are designed to work with these UI elements:
                                - <a> (anchor element)
                                - <form> (form element)

                            Therefore:
                                - Use <a> for navigation => **(GET requests)** => with [HttpGet] methods
                                  > NOT the [HttpPost] methods.
                                - Use <form> + <button type="submit"> for "POST" actions
                                  > The "POST" actions are only triggered using <form method="post">

                            Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/views/tag-helpers/intro
                            
                            For both edit/delete => we need to specify the ID value:
                            > asp-route-id="@instrument.Id" => the current id value to be used by the controller

                            Notice that:
                            - For <a>: The "id" value will be sent via URL (route)
                            - For <form>: The "id" value will be sent via form POST (route + form)
                            So:
                            - <a> => route parameter
                            - <form> => route + form submission

                            Don't forget that:
                             - "instrument" is just a loop variable to reference the current item in the "Model"
                             - "Model" represents the data passed from the controller.
                             - <a> always sends a "GET" request => Example => GET: /Instruments/Delete/7
                                > in such case, we should use [HttpGet] for deleting/editing but not secured, not good practice!
                             - <form method="post"> sends POST requests

                             Consider the following rule again:
                             - Action: Edit (load/viewing the form element - Just retrieving data) => HTTP Method: GET
                             - Action: Edit (submit changes - Modifies data) => HTTP Method: POST
                             - Action: Delete (submit changes - Modifies data) => HTTP Method: POST

                            Therefore:
                                - Edit => uses <a> (GET) to load form
                                - Delete => uses <form> (POST)
                            
                            In such case:
                                > <a> always GET => asp-action="Edit" => calls the "GET" Edit action
                                > <form method="post"> POST => asp-action="Delete" => calls the "POST" Delete action (confirmation page)

                                Example:
                                    GET => Display page
                                    POST => Submit data

                            Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/controllers/actions
                        *@
                        <td>

                            @*
                                The Standard and Correct Industry Flow of using "Edit" Operation:
                                *****************************************************************
                                "Edit" is ALWAYS done in 2 steps:
                                1️) GET => Load Edit page (Load Form)
                                    
                                    [HttpGet]
                                    public IActionResult Edit(int? id)
                                
                                2️) POST => Save changes

                                    [HttpPost]
                                    public IActionResult Edit(Instrument instrument)
                            *@
                            <a class="btn btn-primary me-3" asp-action="Edit" asp-route-id="@instrument.Id">Edit</a>

                            @* 
                              NOTE About Using "Delete" Below: 
                              We will implicitly using the HTTP "POST" request instead of "GET" request,
                              To use the "POST", we need to use <form> with submit <button>,
                              so each action will have its own form:
                            *@

                            @* <a class="btn btn-danger" asp-action="Delete" asp-route-id="@instrument.Id">Delete</a> *@
                            <form asp-action="Delete" asp-route-id="@instrument.Id" method="post" class="d-inline">
                                @Html.AntiForgeryToken()
                                <button type="submit" class="btn btn-danger">Delete</button>
                            </form>

                            @* 
                                BS NOTES:
                                > Adding space between buttons => m-2 = margin-end (Bootstrap spacing of 2 points with any screen size)
                                > using "d-inline"

                                Link: https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.2/utilities/spacing/
                                Link: https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.2/utilities/display/
                            *@

                            @* Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/views/tag-helpers/built-in/anchor-tag-helper?view=aspnetcore-10.0#asp-route-value *@
                        </td>
                    </tr>

                    row++;
                }
            }
        </tbody>
    </table>

    @*
    IMPORTANT NOTE (Summary): HTTP METHODS IN MVC:
    **********************************************

    In ASP.NET Core MVC:

    1) GET request:
       - Used for retrieving data (safe operations only)
       - Triggered by <a> (anchor tags)

    2) POST request:
       - Used for modifying data (Create, Update, Delete)
       - Triggered by <form method="post">

    APPLYING THIS RULE:
    *******************
    - Edit:
        > GET => Load the Edit form (using <a>)
        > POST => Submit updated data (using <form>)

    - Delete:
        > POST only (to safely remove data)
        > Must NOT be triggered by GET

    WHY NOT USE GET FOR DELETE?
    ***************************
    Because GET should NEVER modify data.

    Example of BAD practice:
        GET /Instruments/Delete/5

    This could be triggered accidentally (bookmark, refresh, crawler)

    Therefore:
        > Using <form method="post"> for Delete

    Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/controllers/actions
    *@
</div>